<h2>Ethics Discussion</h2>
While some may disagree with <abbr title="syntactically awesome style sheets">Sass</abbr>, it's up to us believers to keep up the good fight. There's been a great amount of debating and discussion within the community over pre–processing <code>CSS</code> by hiding valuable source code from newbie designers/developers. While that's some food for thought, the fact of the matter is there are plenty of developer tools on the market today that allow for those curious to view the source as well as manipulate it too. Being in the age of handheld, speed wins out over the slim chance a developer is looking under the hood to discover your magical trickery.

In order to achieve speed it means minifying / compressing files and making sure our production code only receives the necessary directives. I remember when I first started using <abbr title="syntactically awesome style sheets">Sass</abbr> with a client project where the <code>CSS</code> was still written in it's native form. After removing all my CSS comments from my production code and <abbr title="syntactically awesome style sheets">Sass</abbr>&ndash;ifying, I shaved 50k off the original file size. Yup, that is a huge savings lifted from the server and our dear users' bandwidth. Not only is that 50K shaved off, but also the end result of the file that's compressed and g–zipped over the wire.

